      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003eWhat are we benefiting from moving to std::Expected here?\n\nBenefit is:\n1. It\u0027s more aligned with modern C++ and at a glance user can see what the API returns on success/failure.\n2. Caller need not create `o_errCode` variable\n3. API implementation need not set `o_errCode \u003d 0;`\n\n\u003eWe still need to create a variable to hold the value returned in std::expected?\nYes, we need a variable.\n\n\u003eIMO std::expected is best suited when the return values are exclusive not when they mean same thing.\n\nThey do not mean same thing. `std::expected\u003cSuccessType, FailureType\u003e` , so on failure it returns `FailureType`.",
